<h2 id="overview">The 3-Year Rule: A Faster Path for Spouses</h2>
<p>Most <SmartLink href="/green-card-through-marriage">green card holders</SmartLink> must wait 5 years before applying for U.S. citizenship. But spouses of U.S. citizens get a significant advantage: you can apply after just <strong>3 years as a lawful permanent resident</strong>, provided you've been continuously married to and living with the same U.S. citizen throughout those 3 years.</p>
<p>This 3-year rule applies whether your green card came through a <SmartLink href="/k1-visa">K-1 fiancé visa</SmartLink> followed by <SmartLink href="/adjustment-of-status">Adjustment of Status</SmartLink>, or directly through a <SmartLink href="/cr1-visa">CR-1 spousal visa</SmartLink>. The clock starts from the date you became a lawful permanent resident — not from your wedding date or your entry date.</p>

<div class="art-info">
  <strong>Conditional green card holders: the clock still counts</strong>
  <p>Time spent as a <SmartLink href="/conditional-green-card">conditional permanent resident</SmartLink> (on a 2-year green card) does count toward the 3-year requirement. You don't need to wait until after your <SmartLink href="/i-751-petition-remove-conditions">I-751 conditions are removed</SmartLink> — you just can't file N-400 until conditions are actually removed and you hold a permanent green card.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="requirements">Full Requirements Checklist</h2>
<p>To naturalize as a spouse of a U.S. citizen under the 3-year rule, you must meet <strong>all</strong> of the following:</p>

<table class="art-table">
  <thead><tr><th>Requirement</th><th>Specifics</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Lawful permanent resident for 3 years</td><td>Green card date must be at least 3 years before N-400 filing</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Married to U.S. citizen for all 3 years</td><td>Same spouse who petitioned for your green card; still legally married at time of naturalization</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Living with U.S. citizen spouse for 3 years</td><td>Living together in a shared residence; separation or divorce disqualifies the 3-year track</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Continuous residence</td><td>No single trip outside the U.S. longer than 6 months; no extended absences that break continuity</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Physical presence</td><td>Present in the U.S. for at least 18 of the 36 months before filing</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Good moral character</td><td>No disqualifying criminal convictions, tax issues, or fraud during the 3-year period</td></tr>
    <tr><td>English language ability</td><td>Pass reading, writing, and speaking portions (with limited exemptions)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>U.S. civics knowledge</td><td>Pass 10-question oral civics interview (answer 6 of 10 correctly)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Attachment to the Constitution</td><td>Swear the Oath of Allegiance at a naturalization ceremony</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2 id="residence">Continuous Residence and Physical Presence Rules</h2>
<p>Two related but different requirements trip up many applicants:</p>

<h3>Continuous Residence</h3>
<p>You must have <strong>continuously resided</strong> in the U.S. for 3 years. A single trip abroad of <strong>more than 6 months</strong> (180+ days) is presumed to break continuous residence — meaning the clock may restart from when you returned. Trips shorter than 6 months are generally fine but add up.</p>
<p>Trips of 6–12 months create a rebuttable presumption of broken continuity — you can provide evidence (job in U.S., family ties, mortgage, taxes) that you maintained your U.S. domicile. Trips over 12 months almost always reset the clock.</p>

<h3>Physical Presence</h3>
<p>Separately, you must have been <strong>physically present</strong> in the U.S. for at least <strong>18 of the 36 months</strong> before filing N-400. This is a counting exercise — add up the days you were inside the U.S. during the 3-year window and ensure they total at least 548 days (18 months).</p>

<div class="art-warn">
  <strong>Track your travel history</strong>
  <p>USCIS will ask you to list every international trip in your N-400 application. Keep a record of every departure and return date starting from when you get your green card. Passport stamps, boarding passes, and calendar records all help.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="tests">The English and Civics Tests</h2>

<h3>English Test</h3>
<p>The English test has three parts, evaluated during your naturalization interview:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Reading:</strong> Read aloud one of three short sentences correctly</li>
  <li><strong>Writing:</strong> Write one of three dictated sentences correctly</li>
  <li><strong>Speaking:</strong> Demonstrated throughout the interview — the officer evaluates your ability to understand questions and respond in English</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Exemptions:</strong> Applicants who are 50+ years old with 20 years as a permanent resident, or 55+ with 15 years, are exempt from the English test (but still take the civics test in their native language).</p>

<h3>Civics Test</h3>
<p>The officer asks up to 10 questions from the official 100-question USCIS civics study list. You need to answer <strong>6 of 10 correctly</strong>. Topics include U.S. history, government structure, rights, and the Constitution. USCIS publishes the full 100-question list for free at <a href="https://www.uscis.gov/citizenship/find-study-materials-and-resources" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">uscis.gov</a> — study it in advance.</p>
<p><strong>Exemptions:</strong> Applicants who are 65+ with 20+ years as a permanent resident take a shorter 20-question version and only need to answer 6 correctly from that reduced set.</p>

<div class="art-cta-mid">
  <h3>Not sure if you qualify for the 3-year track?</h3>
  <p>If your marriage situation has changed — separation, divorce, or a spouse's death — your eligibility path may be different. An attorney can confirm which naturalization track applies to you.</p>
  <a href="#" class="art-btn" data-affiliate="attorney-consult">Get an Attorney Review →</a>
  <a href="/green-card-through-marriage" class="art-btn-outline">Green Card Through Marriage Guide</a>
</div>

<h2 id="n-400">Filing Form N-400</h2>
<p>Naturalization is requested on <strong>Form N-400</strong> (Application for Naturalization). Key details:</p>

<table class="art-table">
  <thead><tr><th>Detail</th><th>Info</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Filing fee</td><td>$760 (includes biometrics); $640 online filing discount available</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Where to file</td><td>Online at <a href="https://my.uscis.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">my.uscis.gov</a> or by mail to the USCIS lockbox</td></tr>
    <tr><td>When you can file</td><td>Up to 90 days before your 3-year anniversary as an LPR</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Documents to include</td><td>Green card copy, marriage certificate, joint tax returns, evidence of living together, travel history, any prior criminal records</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Processing time</td><td>8–18 months (varies by field office)</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<div class="art-info">
  <strong>File up to 90 days early</strong>
  <p>You can submit N-400 up to 90 days before your 3-year anniversary as a permanent resident — USCIS calls this the "early filing window." Filing early means your interview may be scheduled right around your eligibility date, reducing the total wait.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="process">The Naturalization Process After Filing</h2>
<p>After USCIS receives your N-400:</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Biometrics appointment</strong> (4–8 weeks) — fingerprints and photo at an ASC, similar to the <SmartLink href="/biometrics-appointment">AOS biometrics appointment</SmartLink></li>
  <li><strong>Background check</strong> — FBI name check runs in parallel with processing</li>
  <li><strong>Interview notice</strong> (6–14 months) — scheduled at your local USCIS field office</li>
  <li><strong>Naturalization interview</strong> — officer reviews N-400, administers English and civics tests, asks about eligibility</li>
  <li><strong>Decision</strong> — approved at interview, continued (more evidence needed), or denied</li>
  <li><strong>Oath ceremony</strong> — final step; you swear the Oath of Allegiance and receive your Certificate of Naturalization</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="timeline">Full Path Timeline: K-1/CR-1 to U.S. Citizenship</h2>

<table class="art-table">
  <thead><tr><th>Milestone</th><th>Timeline From Start</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>File I-129F (K-1) or I-130 (CR-1)</td><td>Month 0</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Visa approval and entry / CR-1 entry as LPR</td><td>Month 12–30</td></tr>
    <tr><td>K-1: marry + file AOS → conditional green card</td><td>Month 14–36</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Begin 3-year LPR clock</td><td>Green card approval date</td></tr>
    <tr><td>File I-751 to remove conditions (if conditional GC)</td><td>Month 21–24 of green card</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Permanent green card issued after I-751</td><td>+12–36 months after I-751 filing</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Eligible to file N-400 (3-year rule)</td><td>3 years after LPR date</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Naturalization interview + oath</td><td>+8–18 months after N-400</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>U.S. Citizenship</strong></td><td><strong>~5–8 years from K-1 filing</strong></td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="art-faq">
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">How long does a spouse of a U.S. citizen wait before applying for citizenship?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p><strong>3 years</strong> as a lawful permanent resident — provided you've been continuously married to and living with the same U.S. citizen for those 3 years. The standard wait for non-spouses is 5 years.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">What are the main requirements for naturalization?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>3 years as an LPR, continuously married and living with your U.S. citizen spouse, continuous U.S. residence (no trip over 6 months), physical presence for 18 of 36 months, good moral character, passing the English test, and passing the civics test.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">Can I apply for naturalization with a conditional green card?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>Not until after your <SmartLink href="/i-751-petition-remove-conditions">I-751 conditions are removed</SmartLink> and you hold a permanent green card. However, time spent as a conditional resident does count toward the 3-year requirement.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">What is the English test for naturalization?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>Three parts: read one sentence aloud, write one dictated sentence, and demonstrate conversational English during the interview. Exemptions apply for older long-term residents (50+/20 years or 55+/15 years as an LPR).</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">How long does naturalization take after filing N-400?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>Typically <strong>8–18 months</strong> in 2026, depending on your USCIS field office. Check current times at <a href="https://egov.uscis.gov/processing-times/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">egov.uscis.gov/processing-times</a> using form N-400 and your location.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">What is the difference between the 3-year and 5-year rule?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>The 3-year rule applies only to spouses who obtained their green card through marriage to a U.S. citizen and remain married and living together. Everyone else — employment-based, diversity lottery, unmarried children — must wait 5 years.</p></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="art-cta-dark">
  <h2>The journey from visa to citizenship starts with a single petition.</h2>
  <p>Whether you're beginning with a <SmartLink href="/k1-visa">K-1 fiancé visa</SmartLink> or a <SmartLink href="/cr1-visa">CR-1 spousal visa</SmartLink>, the path to U.S. citizenship is the same destination — just different starting points.</p>
